      <div class='hentry member_contribution'>
        <a name='S6CV0372P2_20011017_WH_57'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-harry-cohen' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S6CV0372P2_20011017_WH_57' title='Link to this speech by Mr Harry Cohen' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-harry-cohen" title="Mr Harry Cohen">Harry Cohen</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            There are significant differences between the London Underground PPP and the Railtrack one, but it falls to the Minister to respond to the general thrust of the hon. Gentleman's point.</p><p>
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_268wh' title='Col. 268WH &mdash; HC Deb 17 October 2001 vol 372 c268WH' name='column_268wh' href='#column_268wh' rel='bookmark'>268WH</a>
            In his letter to me of 6 July, Bob Kiley said:
            <q>My negotiations &#x2026; concluded that the current procurement could not be structured to guarantee that new trains would be delivered, that stated investment programs would be carried out, or that maintenance would proceed under standards acceptable to LUL. The only solution was for the bidders to provide LUL with control of core management functions. The bidders could not accept this, leaving no solution within the PPP structure.</q>
            <q>The way forward &#x2026; is to drop the current procurement and take up a safer, quicker and more economic system, bringing massive private-sector participation to clearly defined projects. We can bring new trains and fully repaired tracks to London years ahead of the timescale currently envisaged by PPP. It is a shame that so much time and money has been expended to date on the fruitless negotiations around PPP rather than in progressing a detailed investment programme.</q>
            I urge greater Government flexibility. Private sector involvement and finance is acceptable, but must be under the full control of the public sector. London Underground is a public service, not a profit-making conduit. The proposed version of the PPP seems to contain many flaws. The Mayor will eventually have to take over responsibility for the tube. He was elected to do so. It makes no sense&#x2014;including from a Labour party-political perspective&#x2014;to tie his hands behind his back. We should be at ease with local democracy on matters such as the running of the tube. Even at this late stage, I urge a radical rethink.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
